66
00:06:46,408 --> 00:06:48,414
Whatever helps you sleep at night.

67
00:07:00,438 --> 00:07:02,412
It's almost done, Beth.

68
00:07:02,436 --> 00:07:04,421
They stole you and Matt away from me

69
00:07:04,445 --> 00:07:07,437
but soon they'll pay.

70
00:07:14,452 --> 00:07:17,429
It's okay, Matt. It's okay. Daddy's here.

71
00:07:17,453 --> 00:07:19,460
Shh. Shhshhshh.

72
00:07:23,453 --> 00:07:27,428
How are we gonna pay all these bills?

73
00:07:27,452 --> 00:07:30,452
Don't worry, honey. We'll get through this.

74
00:07:31,467 --> 00:07:34,459
For once, I'm gonna make things right.

75
00:07:36,460 --> 00:07:38,470
Yeah, I'll take a dog with the works.

76
00:07:49,486 --> 00:07:52,472
- 'Night. - Goodnight.

77
00:08:10,505 --> 00:08:13,505
<i>For once, I'm gonna make things right.</i>

78
00:08:16,510 --> 00:08:18,508
Idiot!

79
00:08:31,515 --> 00:08:32,531
Ahh!

80
00:08:48,543 --> 00:08:51,531
Huh? Gas leak!

81
00:08:53,556 --> 00:08:55,546
Run!

82
00:09:03,566 --> 00:09:07,548
Ah, I can't do anything right!

83
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:12,533
Francis Grey was paroled last month

84
00:09:12,557 --> 00:09:14,543
after spending 17 years in prison.

85
00:09:14,567 --> 00:09:17,547
That's a long time to be away from your family.

86
00:09:17,571 --> 00:09:19,552
Apparently, they thought so, too.

87
00:09:19,576 --> 00:09:21,560
His wife left him while he was in prison.

88
00:09:21,584 --> 00:09:24,582
He didn't see her or Matthew again.

89
00:09:25,586 --> 00:09:28,547
Trying to set the time on your VCR?

90
00:09:28,571 --> 00:09:30,549
The atomic clocks in the cave and my suit

91
00:09:30,573 --> 00:09:32,553
should keep perfect synchronized time

92
00:09:32,577 --> 00:09:35,564
yet there's a discrepancy of several seconds between the two.

93
00:09:35,588 --> 00:09:37,559
- Strange. - Uh.

94
00:09:37,583 --> 00:09:38,572
I hate being late, too

95
00:09:38,596 --> 00:09:40,562
but shouldn't we be more concerned

96
00:09:40,586 --> 00:09:42,565
with what Francis has planned with the chemicals?

97
00:09:42,589 --> 00:09:44,570
Grey has most of the base components

98
00:09:44,594 --> 00:09:46,577
to make radium tricholoromethate.

99
00:09:46,601 --> 00:09:48,586
I'm guessing that's not the secret ingredient

100
00:09:48,610 --> 00:09:49,611
in Alfred's eggnog.

101
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:51,590
It's a deadly poison gas.

102
00:09:51,614 --> 00:09:53,587
He needs one more component

103
00:09:53,611 --> 00:09:56,614
and there's only one place in Gotham he can get it.

104
00:10:10,628 --> 00:10:12,599
You okay, Bats?

105
00:10:12,623 --> 00:10:13,611
It's nothing, it's..

106
00:10:13,635 --> 00:10:17,599
Just a sudden sense of deja vu.

107
00:10:17,623 --> 00:10:18,608
Deja what?

108
00:10:18,632 --> 00:10:20,600
It's a French term, describing when you feel

109
00:10:20,624 --> 00:10:22,609
like you've experienced a situation before.

110
00:10:22,633 --> 00:10:26,629
"Robin," by the way, is French for "Duh."

111
00:10:30,645 --> 00:10:33,616
Why is it deadly chemicals are always green?

112
00:10:33,640 --> 00:10:35,648
Why can't they ever be pink?

113
00:10:37,652 --> 00:10:40,627
You're going back to the big house.

114
00:10:40,651 --> 00:10:43,642
- This time for good, Francis. - You know who I am.

115
00:10:43,666 --> 00:10:47,626
Then you know that my prison sentence was totally unfair!

116
00:10:47,650 --> 00:10:50,637
- You committed a crime. - I took a watch!

117
00:10:50,661 --> 00:10:52,632
Everything else was an accident.

118
00:10:52,656 --> 00:10:54,676
For that, they put me away for 17 years?

119
00:10:55,655 --> 00:10:56,653
You make one little mistake..

120
00:10:56,677 --> 00:11:00,682
And you spend the rest of your life paying for it.

121
00:11:01,661 --> 00:11:03,653
- How'd you do that? - I don't know.

122
00:11:03,677 --> 00:11:05,655
We've had this conversation before.

123
00:11:05,679 --> 00:11:07,664
But that's impossible, isn't it?

124
00:11:07,688 --> 00:11:10,654
- Unless.. - Time.

125
00:11:10,678 --> 00:11:11,693
You can manipulate time.

126
00:11:12,672 --> 00:11:14,660
And in such a way, you're the only one aware

127
00:11:14,684 --> 00:11:16,668
you've experienced the previous moment.

128
00:11:16,692 --> 00:11:20,661
It explains the atomic clock discrepancy, the deja vu.

129
00:11:20,685 --> 00:11:22,668
Very good, Batman.

130
00:11:22,692 --> 00:11:24,670
It's easy to become obsessed with time

131
00:11:24,694 --> 00:11:26,675
when that's all you have.

132
00:11:26,699 --> 00:11:28,711
<i>It was all I could think of when I was in prison</i>

133
00:11:29,690 --> 00:11:31,672
<i>all the time that was stolen from me.</i>

134
00:11:31,696 --> 00:11:33,692
<i>And when it became my job to fix all the guard's clocks</i>

135
00:11:33,716 --> 00:11:35,687
<i>I was suddenly surrounded by it.</i>

136
00:11:35,711 --> 00:11:40,685
<i>Seconds, minutes, hours, days, weeks, months, years.</i>

137
00:11:40,709 --> 00:11:42,691
<i>I was so obsessed with the time I was losing</i>

138
00:11:42,715 --> 00:11:47,699
<i>I began to actually see it unravel before me.</i>

139
00:11:47,723 --> 00:11:49,703
Cuckoo, cuckoo!

140
00:11:49,727 --> 00:11:52,721
<i>I thought I was going mad.</i>

141
00:11:55,720 --> 00:11:58,724
Stop!

142
00:12:02,723 --> 00:12:10,731
Huh?

143
00:12:27,769 --> 00:12:30,763
<i>I could turn back time.</i>

144
00:12:32,759 --> 00:12:35,753
<i>I spent every day of the next 15 years working on it.</i>

145
00:12:35,777 --> 00:12:40,752
<i>One second became five seconds. Then 10, then 20.</i>

146
00:12:40,776 --> 00:12:42,779
Whoa! Oh!

147
00:12:45,765 --> 00:12:47,754
<i>I wanted to go back 20 years</i>

148
00:12:47,778 --> 00:12:50,768
<i>before any of this happened.</i>

149
00:12:50,792 --> 00:12:53,761
<i>But all I got was 20 seconds.</i>

150
00:12:53,785 --> 00:12:55,765
I can't get my time back

151
00:12:55,789 --> 00:12:58,767
but I can punish the city for taking it.

152
00:12:58,791 --> 00:13:00,768
You know what time it is now?

153
00:13:00,792 --> 00:13:03,799
Time to kick my sorry butt?

154
00:13:06,790 --> 00:13:08,783
To you, this is all happening for the first time

155
00:13:08,807 --> 00:13:11,787
but we've already had this fight eight..

156
00:13:11,811 --> 00:13:14,816
No, nine. Nine times.

157
00:13:17,809 --> 00:13:20,787
Left hook, right jab, spin kick

158
00:13:20,811 --> 00:13:23,794
flying kick from Batgirl.

159
00:13:23,818 --> 00:13:25,798
Left, right, right, right, left.

160
00:13:25,822 --> 00:13:29,812
Right, right, left, right, left, left, right, kick!

161
00:13:30,819 --> 00:13:33,802
That was fun. Thanks for playing.

162
00:13:33,826 --> 00:13:35,805
Now, if you'll excuse me, I need to make sure

163
00:13:35,829 --> 00:13:39,824
that Gotham rings in the new year with a bang!

164
00:13:55,843 --> 00:13:57,836
I don't care if he's Father Time himself

165
00:13:57,860 --> 00:14:00,850
he is not outrunning us in that.

166
00:14:14,859 --> 00:14:16,878
It's his power, that's how he's outrunning us.

167
00:14:17,857 --> 00:14:18,846
It's like a video game.

168
00:14:18,870 --> 00:14:21,840
He can play the same level over and over again

169
00:14:21,864 --> 00:14:23,854
memorizing every move until he wins.

170
00:14:23,878 --> 00:14:27,847
So everything is a do-over, including our memory.

171
00:14:27,871 --> 00:14:29,861
Then this could be the 10th time we've had this conversation.

172
00:14:29,885 --> 00:14:32,876
Whoa. Brain hurt.

173
00:14:53,911 --> 00:14:56,891
Whoo-hoo!

174
00:14:56,915 --> 00:14:59,921
I'm circling back to 8th street to try and cut him off.

175
00:15:05,926 --> 00:15:08,908
This'll be fun.

176
00:15:10,924 --> 00:15:12,923
I got him.

177
00:15:21,924 --> 00:15:23,937
Here we go.

178
00:15:24,942 --> 00:15:25,945
Not good.

179
00:15:57,972 --> 00:15:59,941
So, how do we stop someone who..

180
00:15:59,965 --> 00:16:02,950
Knows what we're gonna do before we do.

181
00:16:02,974 --> 00:16:03,952
Deja vu again?

182
00:16:03,976 --> 00:16:04,961
It seems to grow stronger

183
00:16:04,985 --> 00:16:07,948
